es:  Vietnamese Hung, Thanh, Minh, Tuan, Dung, Hai, Hoa, Anh, Hoang, Quang, Cuong, Son, Hong, Chi, Sang, Hang, Dong, Man, Chan, Chien, Lai, Ho, Tong, Han, Tam, Nam, Phong, Thai, Tuong, Tinh, Sinh, Chung, Vang, Thach, Uyen, Manh.","Vietnamese (<b>Trần</b>): from the Chinese surname 陳, see   Chen   1.","English and Scottish: variant of   Train  ."]}]},{"name":"Anseau","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adelard, Francois, Jean Pierre, Normand.","French: variant of   Manceau  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Manceau","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: habitational name for someone from Mans, a region in Sarthe, or from Maine, a former province in the northwestern part of France. Compare   Manseau   and English   Mansell   1."]}]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian vernacular form of   Peter ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anseau Ier DE TRAYNEL was born about 1095, in Traînel, Aube, Grand Est, France, his father, Pons DE TRAYNEL, was 46 and his mother, Melisende of Crécy, was 64. He had at least 3 sons a